Part I - Exploring Prosper Loan Data¶

by Jana Alruzuq

Introduction¶

The dataset used in this project is from Prosper, a peer-to-peer lending platform in the United States. It contains detailed information on 113,937 loans including loan amounts, interest rates, borrower income ranges, employment status, credit scores, and loan status.

This analysis will focus on exploring the relationships between loan characteristics and borrower features, aiming to answer questions such as:

  • How are loan amounts distributed across different income levels?
  • Do borrowers with higher Prosper Scores get lower interest rates?
  • Are there differences in interest rates based on employment status?
  • Which loan statuses are most common?

The goal of this exploratory analysis is to uncover patterns, trends, and relationships within the dataset that could be useful for credit risk modeling and financial decision making.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113,937 rows and 81 columns. Most variables are numeric (float or int), with some categorical (object) and boolean features. The data includes loan details, borrower profiles, credit scores, and income-related features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest is the BorrowerRate, which represents the interest rate charged to borrowers. I want to explore what factors influence this rate, such as income level, employment status, ProsperScore, and loan amount.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The main feature of interest is the BorrowerRate, which represents the interest rate charged to borrowers. I want to explore what factors influence this rate, such as income level, employment status, ProsperScore, and loan amount.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, investigate distributions of individual variables. If you see unusual points or outliers, take a deeper look to clean things up and prepare yourself to look at relationships between variables.

1. Distribution of Borrower Rate (Histogram)¶

❓ Question: What is the distribution of Borrower Rates in the dataset?¶

In [3]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.histplot(data=df, x='BorrowerRate', bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Borrower Rate')
plt.xlabel('Borrower Rate')
plt.ylabel('Number of Loans')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Observation:
The distribution of Borrower Rates is slightly right-skewed, with most values falling between 0.1 and 0.25. There is a gradual drop-off after 0.3, and very few loans have rates below 0.05 or above 0.35.

❓ Question: What is the distribution of loan amounts?¶

Observation:
The loan amount distribution shows distinct peaks around specific values such as $4,000, $10,000, and $15,000. These values are likely pre-set loan options. Most loans fall between $2,500 and $15,000, with very few exceeding $25,000. The data is right-skewed with heavy clustering at standard loan sizes.

The majority of borrowers report income ranges between $25,000–49,999 and $50,000–74,999. Very few borrowers are either unemployed or earn less than $25,000. A significant portion of borrowers also chose not to disclose their income.

❓ Question: What are the most common loan statuses?¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The borrower rate distribution is roughly bell-shaped with a peak between 0.15 and 0.2, indicating most borrowers are charged interest in that range. Loan amounts show strong right-skewness, with notable peaks at common requested amounts such as $4,000 and $10,000. While there were some outliers at higher loan amounts, no transformations were applied at this stage to preserve interpretability.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, the loan amount variable showed a heavily skewed distribution with sharp spikes, which likely indicate preset loan options. Additionally, income ranges had a “Not displayed” category with a large count, which could introduce bias. To clean the data, missing or ambiguous income values were flagged for possible exclusion in modeling. However, no transformations were applied to numeric values during univariate exploration.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, investigate relationships between pairs of variables in your data. Make sure the variables that you cover here have been introduced in some fashion in the previous section (univariate exploration).

1. Scatter Plot: Loan Amount vs. Borrower Rate¶

In [7]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='LoanOriginalAmount', y='BorrowerRate', alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Loan Amount vs. Borrower Rate')
plt.xlabel('Loan Amount ($)')
plt.ylabel('Borrower Rate')
plt.show()

Observation: There is a negative relationship between the loan amount and the borrower rate. Borrowers taking smaller loans tend to receive higher interest rates, while larger loans generally come with lower rates. There’s a dense cluster around the $5,000–$15,000 range, indicating this is the most common loan size.

2. Box Plot: Borrower Rate by Loan Status¶

In [8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='LoanStatus', y='BorrowerRate')
plt.title('Borrower Rate by Loan Status')
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
plt.ylabel('Borrower Rate')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Observation: Borrowers whose loans are Completed or Current tend to have lower interest rates. On the other hand, borrowers with Delayed or Defaulted loans have higher borrower rates, indicating that riskier borrowers are charged more interest. Some loan statuses (like “Past Due”) show more outliers and wider variation.

3. Clustered Bar Chart: Loan Status by Income Range¶

In [9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.countplot(data=df, x='IncomeRange', hue='LoanStatus')
plt.title('Loan Status by Income Range')
plt.xlabel('Income Range')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title='Loan Status')
plt.show()

Observation: Most loans were issued to borrowers with income between $25,000 and $74,999. Borrowers with very low or no income (e.g., "Not employed" or "$0") have higher counts of late payments and defaults. Higher income borrowers (e.g., "$100k+") tend to have more completed loans and fewer defaults.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

In this analysis, the main feature of interest was the Borrower Rate. I observed that it has a negative relationship with the Loan Amount — borrowers requesting smaller loans tend to receive higher interest rates. Additionally, when analyzing Loan Status, borrowers with completed or current loans generally had lower borrower rates, while those with defaulted or past-due loans had significantly higher rates. This suggests that the interest rate is likely based on the perceived risk of the borrower.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Yes, one interesting relationship I found was between Income Range and Loan Status. Borrowers with higher income ranges, such as "$100,000+", had a greater proportion of completed loans and fewer defaults, while those with very low or undisclosed income had more delinquencies and charge-offs. This indicates that income level might be a strong predictor of loan repayment behavior.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [13]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Create a FacetGrid to compare Borrower Rate vs Loan Original Amount
# across different Income Ranges, colored by Loan Status
g = sns.FacetGrid(data=df, col="IncomeRange", col_wrap=4, height=4, hue="LoanStatus")
g.map(sns.scatterplot, "LoanOriginalAmount", "BorrowerRate", alpha=0.5)

# Add legend to indicate Loan Status categories
g.add_legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

By using FacetGrid to plot Borrower Rate vs. Loan Amount across different income ranges and colored by loan status, we observed that lower income ranges (e.g., "$1-24,999" and "$0") tend to have higher Borrower Rates regardless of the loan amount. This suggests that income level is a significant factor in determining the interest rate borrowers receive. In contrast, higher income groups (like "$100,000+") show a more concentrated range of lower Borrower Rates. Loan status helps confirm this relationship, as “Chargedoff” and “Defaulted” loans appear more frequently among low-income borrowers with higher rates.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One surprising pattern is how individuals with “Not Employed” or “Not displayed” income ranges still manage to receive loans, though often with higher Borrower Rates. Additionally, the variation in loan status across income groups shows that even high-income borrowers can have loans that are past due or defaulted, indicating that income alone doesn't guarantee repayment success. The spread of Loan Amounts is also wider for high-income borrowers, possibly reflecting higher borrowing capacity.

Conclusions¶

Summary of Main Findings¶

  • Borrower Rate & Loan Amount: Lower-income individuals tend to receive loans with higher borrower rates, while higher-income individuals have access to lower rates, even with higher loan amounts.
  • Loan Status Impact: “Chargedoff” and “Defaulted” loans were more common among low-income borrowers and those with high interest rates.
  • Feature Relationships: Strong relationships were found between income range, borrower rate, and loan status.
  • Unexpected Patterns: Even some high-income borrowers had defaulted loans, and unemployed individuals were still approved for loans, often at higher rates.
  • Visualization Insights: FacetGrid and scatter plots were effective in highlighting multivariate interactions across income, loan amount, and status.
